# Approach
Initialize start and maxLen variables to keep track of the starting index and maximum length of the palindromic substring found.

Loop through each character c in the string s (from index 0 to n-1), treating it as the potential center of a palindrome.

For each center c, expand around it to find the longest palindromic substring. Check for both odd-length and even-length palindromes:

a. Odd-length palindrome: Expand around c by moving the left pointer left towards the left and the right pointer right towards the right, while checking if the characters at s[left] and s[right] are the same.

b. Even-length palindrome: Expand around the center between c and c+1 by moving the left pointer left towards the left and the right pointer right towards the right, while checking if the characters at s[left] and s[right] are the same.

Calculate the length of the palindrome found using right - left - 1.

Compare the length of the current palindrome with the maxLen. If it's greater, update maxLen and calculate the new start index of the longest palindrome.

After iterating through all possible centers, use the start and maxLen to extract the longest palindromic substring using s.substr(start, maxLen).

Return the longest palindromic substring.
