# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Inorder tells which is left half (left subtree) and right half (right subtree)
Preorder tells the order of Node processing

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Populate a HashMap with inorder array which stores element and index.
Call a function which returns TreeNode.
Inside the calling function:
Traverse the preorder array and find its index in HashMap.
Create a new TreeNode for every element in preorder.
Recursively call the function for left half and right half.
Return created TreeNode.
Base Condition:
If left index is greater right index we will return null.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(n)$$

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(n)$$

# Code
```
/**
 * Definition for a binary tree node.
 * public class TreeNode {
 *     int val;
 *     TreeNode left;
 *     TreeNode right;
 *     TreeNode() {}
 *     TreeNode(int val) { this.val = val; }
 *     TreeNode(int val, TreeNode left, TreeNode right) {
 *         this.val = val;
 *         this.left = left;
 *         this.right = right;
 *     }
 * }
 */
class Solution {
    private int preorderIdx = 0;
    private TreeNode construct(int[] preorder, HashMap<Integer,Integer> map, int left, int right){
        if(left>right) return null;
        int pval = preorder[preorderIdx];
        int inorderIdx = map.get(pval);

        TreeNode root = new TreeNode(pval);
        preorderIdx++;
        root.left = construct(preorder, map, left, inorderIdx-1);
        root.right = construct(preorder, map, inorderIdx+1, right);
        return root;

    }
    public TreeNode buildTree(int[] preorder, int[] inorder) {
        HashMap<Integer,Integer> map = new HashMap<>();
        int len = inorder.length;
        for(int i=0;i<len;i++){
            map.put(inorder[i],i);
        }

        return construct(preorder, map, 0, len-1);
    }
}
```

