# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Preorder traversal:$$ \hspace{0.1cm}root --> left \hspace{0.1cm} subtree --> right \hspace{0.1cm} subtree $$
Inorder traversal:$$ \hspace{0.1cm}left \hspace{0.1cm} subtree --> root --> right \hspace{0.1cm} subtree $$

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
> In preorder array, start index is the root node.

In preorder the start index is the root node, so create the node and find that key index in inorder array, let's say that index is `inorder_index`.
Every element in inorder array to the left of inorder_index is part of left sub-tree. And every element to the right of inorder_index is part of right sub-tree.
Call recursion on both left and right sub-tree.

Note: Dry run the solution once for better understanding.

# Optimizations
- Use hashmap to find `inorder_index`.
- Pass start and end index of arrays as parameters.

# Common errors
- Calculating start and end index of preorder array, for left and right subtree.
- Handling base case.

# Complexity
Length of array or number of nodes in tree is $$ n $$.
- Time complexity: $$ O(n) $$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:
    $$ Worst \hspace{0.2cm} case: O(n) $$
    $$ Best \hspace{0.2cm} case: O(log_2n) $$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

